@app.cell
def _(mo):
    mo.md(
        r"""
    ## P61.7

    **Let $F$ be a field, $V = F^2$. We define an equivalence relation on $V - \lbrace 0 \rbrace$ by $v \sim w$ if and only if $v = \alpha w$ for some $\alpha \in F^{\times}$. The set of equivalence classes under this relation is called the one-dimensional projective space (or projective line) over $F$ and is denoted by $\mathbb{P}^1(F)$. We write elements of $V$ as column vectors, and the element of $\mathbb{P}^1(F)$ that is the equivalence class of $\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \end{pmatrix}$ shall be written as $\begin{bmatrix} x\\y \end{bmatrix}$**.

    **Show that there is a well-defined action of $PSL(2, F)$ on $\mathbb{P}^1(F)$ given by** $$\overline{\begin{pmatrix} a&b \\ c&d \end{pmatrix}}\begin{bmatrix} x\\y \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} ax+by\\cx+dy \end{bmatrix}$$ **and that this action is doubly transitive where $\overline{\begin{pmatrix} a&b \\ c&d \end{pmatrix}}$ denotes the image of $\begin{pmatrix} a&b \\ c&d \end{pmatrix} \in SL(2,F)$ in $PSL(2, F)$**.

    Proof

    Follow the axioms:

    1. If $\overline{\begin{pmatrix} a&b \\ c&d \end{pmatrix}} = 1 \in PSL(2,F)$ then $b = c = 0$ and $a = d$, so $\overline{\begin{pmatrix} a&b \\ c&d \end{pmatrix}}\begin{bmatrix} x\\y \end{bmatrix}$ $= \begin{bmatrix} ax\\ay \end{bmatrix}$ $= \begin{bmatrix} x\\y \end{bmatrix}$;
    2. $\overline{\begin{pmatrix} a'&b' \\ c'&d' \end{pmatrix}}(\overline{\begin{pmatrix} a&b \\ c&d \end{pmatrix}}\begin{bmatrix} x\\y \end{bmatrix})$ $=\overline{\begin{pmatrix} a'&b' \\ c'&d' \end{pmatrix}}\begin{bmatrix} ax+by\\cx+dy \end{bmatrix}$ $=\begin{bmatrix} a'(ax+by) + b'(cx+dy)\\c'(ax+by)+d'(cx+dy) \end{bmatrix}$, on the other hand $(\overline{\begin{pmatrix} a'&b' \\ c'&d' \end{pmatrix}}\overline{\begin{pmatrix} a&b \\ c&d \end{pmatrix}})\begin{bmatrix} x\\y \end{bmatrix}$ $=\overline{\begin{pmatrix} a'a+b'c&a'b+b'd \\ c'a+d'c&c'b+d'd \end{pmatrix}}\begin{bmatrix} x\\y \end{bmatrix}$ $=\begin{bmatrix} (a'a+b'c)x + (a'b+b'd)y\\(c'a+d'c)x+(c'b+d'd)y \end{bmatrix}$, so they are the same.

    (the point in part 2 is that the quotient image of product is the same as the product of quotient image, which is true since $G/N \times G/N \cong (G \times G)/(N \times N)$)

    For doubly transitivity, essentially for $\begin{bmatrix} x_1\\y_1 \end{bmatrix}\ne\begin{bmatrix} x_3\\y_3 \end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix} x_2\\y_2 \end{bmatrix}\ne\begin{bmatrix} x_4\\y_4 \end{bmatrix} \in\mathbb{P}^1(F)$ we want to find $\overline{\begin{pmatrix} a&b \\ c&d \end{pmatrix}}$ so that $\begin{cases} ax_1+by_1 = x_2 \\ cx_1 + dy_1 = y_2 \\ ax_3+by_3 = x_4 \\ cx_3+dy_3 = y_4 \end{cases}$. We can write this system as $\begin{pmatrix} x_1&y_1 \\ x_3&y_3 \end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix} a&c \\ b&d \end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix} x_2&y_2 \\ x_4&y_4 \end{pmatrix}$. By assumption the determinant of $\begin{pmatrix} x_1&y_1 \\ x_3&y_3 \end{pmatrix}$ (and $\begin{pmatrix} x_2&y_2 \\ x_4&y_4 \end{pmatrix}$) is never $0$ so we always have a solution.

    The only problem is that if we directly solve this system and $\det{\begin{pmatrix} x_1&y_1 \\ x_3&y_3 \end{pmatrix}} \ne \det{\begin{pmatrix} x_2&y_2 \\ x_4&y_4 \end{pmatrix}}$ then $\det{\begin{pmatrix} a&b \\ c&d \end{pmatrix}} \ne 1$ (determinant of product is product of determinant) so it is in $PGL$ but not in $PSL$. In this case, say $\det{\begin{pmatrix} x_1&y_1 \\ x_3&y_3 \end{pmatrix}} = a \in F$ and $\det{\begin{pmatrix} x_2&y_2 \\ x_4&y_4 \end{pmatrix}} = b \in F$, with $a\ne b$, then $a^{-1}b \in F$ (it is not $0$ because a field does not have zero divisor). Replace $\begin{pmatrix} x_1\\y_1 \end{pmatrix}$ by $\begin{pmatrix} a^{-1}bx_1\\a^{-1}by_1 \end{pmatrix}$ so it is still in the same equivalence class, then the solution will necessarily be in $PSL$, thus we have double transitivity.

    ## P61.9

    **Let $F$ be the field of $7$ elements. For $0 \le i \le 6$ let $i$ represent $\begin{bmatrix}1 \\i  \end{bmatrix} \in \mathbb{P}^1(F)$; denote the remaining element $\begin{bmatrix}0\\1  \end{bmatrix}$ of $\mathbb{P}^1(F)$ by $\infty$. View $S_8$ as being the group of permutations of $\lbrace \infty,0,\dots,6 \rbrace$ and let $\varphi:PSL(2,7) \to S_8$ be the monomorphism arising as in Proposition 3.1 from the action of $PSL(2,7)$ on $\mathbb{P}^1(F)$. Show that the image of $\varphi$ is the subgroup of $A_8$ generated by $(0 123456)$, $(142)(356)$ and $(\infty 0)(13)(25)(46)$**.

    Proof

    We know $PSL(2,7)$ is simple, so the image of $PSL(2,7)$ under $\varphi$ would be a subgroup of $A_8$ (because determinant $=1$ corresponds to even permutations) that is isomorphic to $PSL(2,7)$.

    (The image of natural projection of) the matrix $\begin{pmatrix} 1&0\\1&1 \end{pmatrix}$ is of course an element in $PSL(2,7)$. On the other hand, consider the (set-wise) stabilizer of $\lbrace 0,\infty \rbrace$:

    By some direct matrix multiplication calculation, if we want to map $0 \mapsto 0$ and $\infty \mapsto \infty$, i.e. $\begin{pmatrix} a&b\\c&d \end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix} 1\\0 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} x\\0 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\begin{pmatrix} a&b\\c&d \end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix} 0\\1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 0\\y \end{pmatrix}$, then $b$ and $c$ are forced to be $0$, and $a,d$ are inverse of each other because the matrix has determinant $1$, i.e. we need a matrix of the form $\begin{pmatrix} x&0\\0&x^{-1} \end{pmatrix}$, those matrices are generated by $\begin{pmatrix} 2&0\\0&4 \end{pmatrix}$; and if we want to map $0 \mapsto \infty$ and $\infty \mapsto 0$ then similarly we need a matrix of the form $\begin{pmatrix} 0&-x^{-1}\\x&0 \end{pmatrix}$, those are generated by $\begin{pmatrix} 0&3\\2&0 \end{pmatrix}$.

    Apparently $\begin{pmatrix} 1&0\\1&1 \end{pmatrix}$ cannot be generated by the other two matrices. Since stabilizer of doubly transitive action is maximal (we proved this statement for stabilizer of single point, but it is really the same argument for the set-wise stabilizer), the group $\langle \begin{pmatrix} 1&0\\1&1 \end{pmatrix}, \begin{pmatrix} 2&0\\0&4 \end{pmatrix}, \begin{pmatrix} 0&3\\2&0 \end{pmatrix} \rangle$ (under the natural projection) must be the whole $PSL(2,7)$. So the isomorphic image of $PSL(2,7)$ inside $A_8$ must be generated by the permutations induced by those three matrices.

    It is then not hard to verify they correspond to $(0123456)$, $(124)(365)$ (it is the same as $(142)(356)$, just replace $\begin{pmatrix} 2&0\\0&4 \end{pmatrix}$ with $\begin{pmatrix} 4&0\\0&2 \end{pmatrix}$)and $(\infty 0)(13)(25)(46)$ as desired.

    ## P80.4

    **Let $U$ be the subgroup of $GL(n,p)$ consisting of the upper uni-triangular matrices, and let $Q$ be the subgroup of $U$ consisting of all matrices whose $(i,j)$ entry is zero whenever $1 < i < j < n$. Determine $Z(Q)$, and show that $Q/Z(Q)$ is abelian**.

    Proof

    By assumption, $Q$ is the group such that a generic element looks like $$\begin{pmatrix} 1&a_{12}&a_{13}&\dots&a_{1~n-1}&a_{1n} \\ 0&1&0&\dots&0&a_{2n} \\ 0&0&1&\dots&0&a_{3 n}\\ \dots&\dots&\dots&\dots&\dots&\dots\\ 0&0&0&\dots&1&a_{n-1~n}\\ 0&0&0&\dots&0&1\end{pmatrix},$$ i.e. matrices with $1$ on the diagonal, arbitrary on the first row and last column (except for the top left and bottom right corner, of course), and $0$ everywhere else.

    $Z(Q)$ is by definition those $Z \in Q$ such that $ZM = MZ$ for $M \in Q$. Let's denote the terms of $Z$ by $z_{ij}$, of $M$ by $m_{ij}$, and just do some matrices multiplication. It is not very hard to see that (for a fixed $Z$): $ZM = MZ$ if and only if $z_{12}m_{2n} + z_{13}m_{3n}+\dots +z_{1~n-1}m_{n-1~n}$ $= m_{12}z_{2n} + m_{13}z_{3n}+\dots +m_{1~n-1}z_{n-1~n}$, for **all** $M \in Q$, so the only choice is to have all those $z_{ij}$'s to be $0$. The term we are not touching is $z_{1n}$, so a generic element of $Z(Q)$ is a matrix with $1$ on the diagonal, arbitrary on the top right corner, and $0$ everywhere else.

    The center is always a normal subgroup, so the quotient is always a group, we just need to show it is abelian.

    Notice if we multiply a matrix by such $Z$, we merely add $z_{1n}$ to the top right corner of the original matrix $$\begin{pmatrix} 1&a_{12}&a_{13}&\dots&a_{1~n-1}&\boxed{a_{1n}} \\ 0&1&0&\dots&0&a_{2n} \\ 0&0&1&\dots&0&a_{3 n}\\ \dots&\dots&\dots&\dots&\dots&\dots\\ 0&0&0&\dots&1&a_{n-1~n}\\ 0&0&0&\dots&0&1\end{pmatrix} \mapsto \begin{pmatrix} 1&a_{12}&a_{13}&\dots&a_{1~n-1}&\boxed{a_{1n}+z_{1n}} \\ 0&1&0&\dots&0&a_{2n} \\ 0&0&1&\dots&0&a_{3 n}\\ \dots&\dots&\dots&\dots&\dots&\dots\\ 0&0&0&\dots&1&a_{n-1~n}\\ 0&0&0&\dots&0&1\end{pmatrix}.$$ It means each coset in the quotient consists precisely all matrices that only differ at the top right corner, and we may choose to use the matrices with $0$ at the top right corner to represent each coset.

    Now if we multiply $A, B \in Q$ in two ways $A B$ and $B A$, it is not hard to see the result differs only possibly at the top right corner, but we chose to force the top right corner to be zero, so the result is always the same in the quotient group, and thus the group is abelian as desired.

    ## P80.6

    **Let $U$ be the subgroup of $GL(3, p)$ consisting of the upper uni-triangular matrices. Show that if $p$ is an odd prime, then $U$ is a non-abelian group of order $p^3$ having no elements of order $p^2$. If $p = 2$, with which group of order $8$ is $U$ isomorphic**?

    Proof

    $U = \lbrace \begin{pmatrix} 1&a&b\\0&1&c\\0&0&1\end{pmatrix} | a,b,c \in \mathbb{Z}_p \rbrace$, so $| U | = p^3$ because each $a,b,c$ can be chose from $p$ different elements. Consider the matrices $A = \begin{pmatrix} 1&1&0 \\ 0&1&0 \\ 0&0&1 \end{pmatrix}$ and $B = \begin{pmatrix} 1&0&0\\0&1&1\\0&0&1 \end{pmatrix}$, then $A, B \in U$ and we can calculate $AB = \begin{pmatrix} 1&1&1\\0&1&1\\0&0&1 \end{pmatrix}$ $\ne \begin{pmatrix} 1&1&0\\0&1&1 \\0&0&1 \end{pmatrix}=BA$, so $U$ is not abelian.

    Moreover, if $p$ is odd, a direct calculation gives $\begin{pmatrix} 1&a&b\\0&1&c\\0&0&1 \end{pmatrix}^p$ $=\begin{pmatrix} 1&pa&pb+\sum\limits_{i=1}^{p-1}i\cdot ac \\ 0&1&pc \\ 0&0&1 \end{pmatrix}$ which equals the identity matrix already for any $a,b,c$, because the coefficient are all divisible by $p$ ($\sum\limits_{i=1}^{p-1}i$ $= 1+2+\dots+p-1$, add first with last, second to second-last, etc, since $p$ is odd, this equals $p+p+\dots+p$ is divisible by $p$). Thus any matrix in $U$ has at most order $p$, thus cannot have order $p^2$.

    If $p = 2$, we may identify $$\begin{pmatrix} 1&0&0 \\ 0&1&0 \\ 0&0&1 \end{pmatrix} = 1,\begin{pmatrix} 1&1&0 \\ 0&1&0 \\ 0&0&1 \end{pmatrix} = a,\begin{pmatrix} 1&0&1 \\ 0&1&0 \\ 0&0&1 \end{pmatrix} = b$$ and verify that $a^4 = b^2 = 1$, $b^{-1}ab = a^{-1}$, and that this group is isomorphic to the dihedral group $D_4$.

    ## P174.9

    **Let $G = GL(2, q)$ where $q$ is any prime power. Then $| G | = q(q-1)^2(q+1)$. Denote by $m_g(X)$ the minimal polynomial of an element $g \in G$. Show that if $m_g(X) = X-a$ for some $a \in \mathbb{F}_q^{\times}$, then $g = \begin{pmatrix} a&0\\0&a \end{pmatrix} \in Z(G)$**.

    Proof

    We will be doing several matrices multiplications and solve several systems. For convenience, say $g = \begin{pmatrix} x&y\\z&w \end{pmatrix}$ in matrix form.

    By assumption we have $g - aI = 0$, i.e. $$\begin{pmatrix} x&y\\z&w \end{pmatrix}-\begin{pmatrix} a&0\\0&a \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 0&0\\0&0 \end{pmatrix}$$ so $x = a$, $y = 0$, $z = 0$, and $w = a$, thus $g$ is of the form $\begin{pmatrix} a&0\\0&a \end{pmatrix}$. Since $g$ of this form can be written as $aI$ with inverse $\frac{1}{a}I$, it must lie in the center. In particular, those $g$'s are in their own conjugacy classes, and there are $q-1$ of them, one for each $a$.

    ## P174.10

    **Show that if $m_g(X) = (X-a)^2$ for some $a \in \mathbb{F}_q^{\times}$, then $g$ is conjugate with $\begin{pmatrix} a&1\\0&a \end{pmatrix}$, and the conjugacy class of $g$ has order $q^2 - 1$**.

    Proof

    Expand $(g-aI)^2 = 0$, we will get a system $$\begin{cases} (x-a)^2+yz &= 0\\ y(w+x-2a) &= 0\\z(w+x-2a) &=0\\ (w-a)^2+yz &= 0\end{cases}.$$ Since $m_g(X)$ is assumed not $X-a$, we cannot have both $y, z = 0$. If they are both not zero, then $x=w = \sqrt{-yz}+a \ne a$ but $x+w = 2a$, which is impossible. So one of them is zero and the other is not, so $g$ is of the form $$g = \begin{pmatrix} a&b\\0&a \end{pmatrix}\text{ or }\begin{pmatrix} a&0\\b&a \end{pmatrix}, b \ne 0.$$ It is not hard to verify they are both conjugate to $\begin{pmatrix} a&1\\0&a \end{pmatrix}$, for example: $$\begin{pmatrix} b&0\\0&1 \end{pmatrix}^{-1}\begin{pmatrix} a&b\\0&a \end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix} b&0\\0&1 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} a&1\\0&a \end{pmatrix}.$$ To see the order of the conjugacy class, by direct calculation it is not hard to see the stabilizer of $\begin{pmatrix} a&1\\0&a \end{pmatrix}$ is of the form $\begin{pmatrix} x&y\\0&x \end{pmatrix}$; $x$ can be taken in $\mathbb{F}_q^{\times}$ and $y$ is completely arbitrary, so the order of the stabilizer is $q(q-1)$, thus orbit-stabilizer theorem tells us the order of the conjugacy class is $(q-1)(q+1) = q^2-1$.

    There are $q-1$ of such conjugacy classes, one for each $a$.

    ## P174.11

    **Show that if $m_g(X) = (X-a)(X-b)$ for some distinct $a,b \in \mathbb{F}_q^{\times}$ then $g$ is conjugate with $\begin{pmatrix} a&0\\0&b \end{pmatrix}$ and the conjugacy class of $g$ has order $q^2+q$**.

    Proof

    Similarly we get a system $$\begin{cases}ab+x^2-ax-bx+yz &= 0 \\ y(x+w-a-b) &= 0 \\ z(x+w-a-b) &= 0 \\ ab+w^2-aw-bw+yz &= 0\end{cases}.$$ Suppose $y,z$ are both non-zero, then $x,w = \frac{a+b\pm\sqrt{\dots}}{2}$ by quadratic formula, but a matrix of this form is conjugate to $\begin{pmatrix} \frac{a+b}{2}&1 \\ 0&\frac{a+b}{2} \end{pmatrix}$ and falls in the above category. Otherwise at least one of $y,z$ is zero, forcing $x = a, w =b$ or $w =a, x= b$. A direct calculation shows that matrices of the form $$\begin{pmatrix} a&0\\0&b \end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix} b&0\\0&a \end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix} a&c\\0&b \end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix} a&0\\c&b \end{pmatrix}$$ are all in the same conjugacy class, as desired.

    The order of the conjugacy class is calculated in a similar manner as well. We may calculate $$\begin{pmatrix} x&y\\z&w \end{pmatrix}^{-1}\begin{pmatrix} a&0\\0&b \end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix} x&y\\z&w \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{awx-byz}{wx-yz}&\frac{awy-bwy}{wx-yz}\\\frac{-axz+bxz}{wx-yz}&\frac{bwx-ayz}{wx-yz} \end{pmatrix},$$ we can see the stabilizer consists of matrix of the form $\begin{pmatrix} x&0\\0&w \end{pmatrix}$ where $x,w \in \mathbb{F}_q^{\times}$ so has order $(q-1)^2$, and thus the conjugacy class has order $q(q+1) = q^2+q$.

    There are $(q-1)(q-2)/2$ of distinct unordered such $a,b$, so there are $(q-1)(q-2)$ such conjugacy classes.

    ## P174.12

    **Show that if $r,s \in \mathbb{F}_q$ are such that $X^2-rX-s$ is irreducible, then the conjugacy class of $\begin{pmatrix} 0&1\\s&r \end{pmatrix}$ has order $q^2-q$**.

    Proof

    Similarly we have a system $$\begin{cases}x^2-rx+yz-s &= 0 \\ y(x+w-r) &= 0 \\ z(x+w-r) &= 0 \\ w^2-rw+yz-s &= 0\end{cases}.$$ It is impossible to have at least one of $y,z$ being zero, because that forces $x^2-rx-s =0$, which is an irreducible quadratic polynomial, implies that $x \notin \mathbb{F}_{q}$. So neither of $y,z$ is zero. Now if $yz \ne s$, or equivalently if both $x,w$ are not zero, then this matrix is conjugate to a certain matrix in category $2$; so $yz=s$ and one of $x,w$ is $r$, the other is $0$. It is not hard to verify $$\begin{pmatrix} 0&1\\s&r \end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix} r&1\\s&0 \end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix} 0&a\\s/a&r \end{pmatrix},\begin{pmatrix} r&a\\s/a&0 \end{pmatrix}$$ are all conjugate, as desired.

    Again we count the stabilizer, by considering $$\begin{aligned}\begin{pmatrix} x&y\\z&w \end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix} 0&1\\s&r \end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix} sy&x+ry\\sw&rw+z \end{pmatrix}\\=\begin{pmatrix} z&w\\sx+rz&rw+sy \end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix} 0&1\\s&r \end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix} x&y\\z&w \end{pmatrix}\end{aligned},$$ we either have $x=w, y=z = 0$ (there are $q-1$ of such) or $y =z/s = (w-x)/r$, where if $y \in \mathbb{F}_q^{\times}$ and $w \in \mathbb{F}_q$ are chosen, $x,z$ are fixed. In total the order of stabilizer is $(q-1)(q+1)$ thus order of conjugacy class is $q^2-q$.

    The number of such conjugacy class is the same as the number of irreducible monic quadratic polynomials in $\mathbb{F}_q$, which equals $q^2$ (total number of monic polynomial) minus $\frac{q(q+1)}{2}$ (number of polynomials of the form $(x-r)(x-s)$ or $(x-r)^2$, i.e. reducible ones), which equals $q(q-1)/2$.

    ## P174.13

    **Verify that what follows is a complete list of the conjugacy classes of $G$: $q-1$ classes of $1$ element each, indexed by elements of $\mathbb{F}_q^{\times}$; $q-1$ classes of $q^2-1$ elements each, indexed by elements of $\mathbb{F}_q^{\times}$; $(q-1)(q-2)/2$ classes of $q^2+q$ elements each, indexed by unordered pairs of distinct elements of $\mathbb{F}_q^{\times}$; and $q(q-1)/2$ classes of $q^2-q$ elements each, indexed by irreducible monic quadratic polynomials with coefficients in $\mathbb{F}_q$**.

    Proof

    This is an immediate result followed by preceding problems, and just to make sure: calculate $$\begin{aligned}(q-1)\cdot 1 + (q-1)\cdot(q^2-1) \\+ (q-1)(q-2)(q^2+q)/2 + q(q-1)&(q^2-q)/2 \\&= q(q-1)^2(q+1)\end{aligned}$$ so indeed we have everything covered.
    """
    )
    return


